<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2011/02/17/spring-3-1-m1-introducing-featurespecification-support">Spring 3.1 M1: Introducing FeatureSpecification support</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/1e63dcf15fa29bebc0c68bc4d28b87e6?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<span class="author">Chris Beams</span>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2011-02-17 00:58:00.0">February 17, 2011</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="397" href="/blog/2011/02/17/spring-3-1-m1-introducing-featurespecification-support#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p><em>UPDATE: The <code>FeatureSpecification</code> functionality described in this blog post was removed in Spring Framework 3.1 M2 in favor of <code>@Enable*</code> annotations. See the <a href="http://blog.springsource.org/2011/06/10/spring-3-1-m2-configuration-enhancements">3.1 M2 announcement</a> for more information.</em></p>
<h3>Introduction</h3>
<p>Earlier <a href="http://blog.springsource.com/2011/02/11/spring-framework-3-1-m1-released/">in</a> <a href="http://blog.springsource.com/2011/02/14/spring-3-1-m1-introducing-profile/">this</a> <a href="http://blog.springsource.com/2011/02/15/spring-3-1-m1-unified-property-management/">series</a> I touched on how the new <code>@Profile</code> annotation can be used in conjunction with <code>@Configuration</code> classes to take advantage of Spring’s <em>bean definition profiles</em>. Today, we’ll look at an entirely new addition to the code-based configuration landscape in Spring 3.1: <em><code>FeatureSpecification</code> classes</em> and their related support.</p>
</div>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore desktop-only" href="/blog/2011/02/17/spring-3-1-m1-introducing-featurespecification-support">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
